## V. THE THERMODYNAMIC CONSTRAINT: THE OPTIMIZATION PRINCIPLE

Every serious theory must state its limits explicitly. A framework that cannot be falsified is philosophy. A framework that ignores its constraints is science fiction. The IISL is governed by a hard constraint that must stand at the center of the paper:

> **Intrinsic scaling must obey biological thermodynamics. Therefore, optimization — not expansion — is its governing principle.**

The brain cannot simply grow larger or run hotter. The skull is a fixed enclosure. Oxygen delivery and glucose metabolism impose hard ceilings on raw computational expansion. Heat dissipation at 37°C limits operating frequency. These are thermodynamic laws, not engineering challenges.

This constraint is not a weakness of the carbon-first framework. It is its defining strength. The IISL is formulated precisely around this constraint: the optimization target is the ratio **I = k(B^α · C^β)/E^γ**, not the numerator alone. A biological system that doubles its integration and coherence while halving its metabolic waste has achieved a genuine scaling event. One that simply consumes more glucose is not scaling. It is burning.

The carbon-first path does not pursue unlimited growth. It pursues **maximum intelligence per unit of thermodynamic cost**. The human brain at 20 watts, running at an estimated fraction of its theoretical maximum efficiency, is already the best known solution to this optimization problem in the universe. The eight pillars of this framework are not attempts to violate the thermodynamic ceiling. They are attempts to approach it.

