## VIII. COMPETING FRAMEWORKS: WHY THE ALTERNATIVES FAIL

The Carbon-First Intelligence framework must be positioned against the most sophisticated competing proposals. We identify four: whole brain emulation, organoid intelligence, silicon-biological hybrid interfaces, and silicon neuromorphic scaling. We demonstrate that each fails on the IISL's terms.

### VIII.1 Whole Brain Emulation

Whole brain emulation (WBE) proposes uploading the full connectivity map of a biological brain into a silicon substrate, preserving the information structure of biological intelligence while gaining the speed and replicability of silicon.

The IISL identifies the fundamental error. WBE preserves the **information pattern** of the brain while discarding its **substrate**. Under IIT's formalism, what matters for consciousness is not the abstract pattern but the specific causal structure of the physical substrate that instantiates it. A silicon simulation of the brain's connectivity map does not inherit the brain's Φ. It inherits its own Φ — which, given silicon's architectural constraints, will be substantially lower for any given energy budget.

WBE is the maximum case of Substrate Partition Failure: not partial offloading, but complete substrate replacement. Under the IISL, any WBE system will score high on B (it has all the connectivity information) but low on C (it lacks the causal structure that generates Φ in biological tissue). Current progress confirms the energy gap: China's Darwin Monkey supercomputer, one of the most advanced neuromorphic platforms, uses approximately 2,000 watts — 100 times the biological brain's 20 watts — and remains orders of magnitude below biological cognitive flexibility.

### VIII.2 Organoid Intelligence

The Johns Hopkins Brainoware project and related organoid intelligence programs grow biological neural tissue in vitro and connect it to silicon computing systems as a biological co-processor.

The IISL identifies two failure modes. First, an organoid without embodiment, homeostasis, continuous sensory input, and metabolic embedding lacks the continuous temporal anchoring that generates high Φ. It scores high on the structural components of B but low on C — high connectivity, low coherence, no unified experience. Second, connecting it to silicon as a peripheral processor reintroduces the Hybrid Fallacy: the biological component becomes a dependent node in a partitioned system, and the silicon cannot provide the homeostatic and interoceptive integration that generates biological coherence. The organoid becomes a biological calculator — architecturally interesting, experientially hollow.

There is also an ethical dimension that the IISL framework notes without resolving: bioethicists have argued that if organoid biocomputers achieve consciousness, they acquire moral status, which places substantial constraints on permissible research. The fundamental question — can intelligent behavior be meaningfully separated from an intelligent being — is not rhetorical. It is a genuine scientific and ethical boundary that organoid intelligence research has not yet addressed.

