## XIII. ETHICS ARCHITECTURE: SAFETY, REVERSIBILITY, AND EQUITY

A framework proposing to engineer human intelligence must address ethics not as a footnote but as a structural component. The following constraints are not negotiable additions to the framework. They are part of the framework.

**Epigenetic reversibility.** All CRISPRa modifications proposed in this framework are epigenetic — they alter gene expression without altering DNA sequence. They are reversible via CRISPRi (the inhibitory counterpart) or via small-molecule inhibitors targeting the dCas9 fusion protein. No permanent genomic change is required for any pillar except Pillar 3 (Dsup/TRID1 integration), which requires stable somatic genomic insertion. For Pillar 3, inducible promoter systems (doxycycline-on AAV constructs) provide temporal control and reversible expression.

**Somatic-only deployment.** No pillar requires germline modification. All eight hypotheses test somatic models. No changes heritable by future generations are proposed or required.

**WHO 2025 compliance.** The WHO global recommendations for human genome editing distinguish therapeutic from enhancement applications and somatic from germline modifications, emphasizing ethical and equitable use. The carbon-first framework operates within the somatic enhancement quadrant. All human applications will require regulatory approval under existing frameworks (FDA, EMA, national equivalents) and proposed minimum 10-year longitudinal safety follow-up.

**The equity problem.** The most serious ethical challenge to the carbon-first framework is not safety — it is equity. If enhancements are available only to wealthy individuals or nations, the framework risks producing a two-tier species: Homo Intellectus and everyone else. The framework explicitly states that this outcome would be a catastrophic failure mode, not a success condition. Any implementation pathway must include explicit equity provisions. The open-source DNA framework proposed in Section VII's DIE architecture explicitly anticipates this: directed intrinsic evolution must be democratized or it becomes the most dangerous form of inequality ever invented. This is not a solved problem. It is a design requirement that future versions of this framework must address in detail.

**The wisdom requirement.** Intelligence without wisdom is the most dangerous possible outcome of this framework. Homo Intellectus is defined not only by elevated B and C but by the preservation of the ethical, emotional, and interoceptive architecture that generates wisdom. The eight parameters of the endpoint explicitly include interoceptive precision (Parameter 7) because interoception — the body's direct representation of its own states, including moral discomfort, empathy, and relational attunement — is the biological substrate of conscience. Engineering intelligence while degrading interoception would produce exactly the misaligned superintelligence that the silicon-first path risks. The carbon-first framework is immune to this failure mode only if its implementation preserves and enhances the biological systems that generate values alongside the systems that generate intelligence.

